Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUXELLES – Russia's takeover of Crimea is the most serious example of peacetime aggression that Europe has experienced since Germany's Nazi annexation of the Sudetenland in 1938.
It is certainly now common to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier gave in to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to pacify the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might greatly regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – such as expulsion from the G8, for example – might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin views the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most serious catastrophe of modern times, a man tirelessly striving to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
The many successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative for a Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to bring a number of resource-rich states into its fold, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And now comes the most precious geostrategic trophy of all – Ukraine – which could well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by former American National Security Advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a Ukraine that is first seduced and then subordinated, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's response be commensurate with the degree of adventurism demonstrated by Putin.
Cancellations of summits, trade agreement proposals, and other participations in as unproductive forums as the G8 would not be enough.
Only measures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions that could affect Russian citizens – who, remember, continue to re-elect Putin to power – could allow us to hope that the Kremlin will abandon its expansionist course.
What kind of sanctions could they be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russia-Georgia war.
At the time, Turkey blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent America from intervening, although it is now clearly apparent that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports on the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military ambitions – would be significant.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the Montreux Convention of 1936.
Turkey could thus turn against Putin the very motive he invoked to justify the takeover of Crimea – namely that he would protect the Russian ethnic groups living there – by asserting that it itself is protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar descent, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back in mid-air in order to head to Kiev to support the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not exactly a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian traffic – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so that they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia seeks to intimidate it.
Secondly, American President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions indeed significantly undermined Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would create an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the scarcity of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist agenda could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true tragedy in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was the greatest geostrategic windfall that China could imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had taken millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners for China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously displeased China, as evidenced by China's stance during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held following the war (this regional grouping comprising several former Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia attempted to persuade the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the Organization expressed its disagreement.
Indeed, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have opposed the Kremlin without China's support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction avenues are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas denied or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, and particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is waging today could fail.
The price of inaction could well prove to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this American promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had the choice between war and dishonor.
You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are now faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
